    <div xml:id="PN387">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>vaḷḷukira vayalāmai</l>
<l>veḷḷakaṭu kaṇṭaṉṉa</l>
<l>vīṅkuvicip putuppōrvait</l>
<l>teṇkaṇ mākkiṇai yiyakki yeṉṟu</l>
<l>māṟukoṇṭōr matiliṭaṟi</l>
<l>nīṟāṭiya naṟuṅkavuḷa</l>
<l>pūmpoṟi paṇaiyeruttiṉa</l>
<l>vēṟuvēṟu parantiyaṅki</l>
<l>vēntuṭaimiḷai yayalparakku</l>
<l>mēntukōṭ ṭirumpiṇar taṭakkait</l>
<l>tiruntutoḻiṟ palapakaṭu</l>
<l>pakaippula maṉṉar paṇitiṟai tantuniṉ</l>
<l>ṉakaippula vāṇar nalkura vakaṟṟi</l>
<l>mikappoliyartaṉ cēvaṭi yattaiyeṉ</l>
<l>ṟiyāṉicaippi ṉaṉinaṉṟeṉāp</l>
<l>palapiṟa vāḻtta viruntō reṉkō<gap quantity="15" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l>maruvaviṉaka rakaṉ<gap quantity="33" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l>tiruntukaḻaṟ cēvaṭi kuṟukal vēṇṭi</l>
<l>veṉṟiraṅkum viṟaṉmuraciṉō</l>
<l>ṉeṉciṟumaiyi ṉiḻittunōkkāṉ</l>
<l>taṉperumaiyiṟ ṟakavunōkkik</l>
<l>kuṉṟuṟaḻnta kaḷiṟeṉkō</l>
<l>koyyuḷaiya māveṉkō</l>
<l>maṉṟuniṟaiyu niraiyeṉkō</l>
<l>maṉaikkaḷamaroṭu kaḷameṉkō</l>
<l>vāṅkavai, kaṉaveṉa maruḷa vallē naṉavi</l>
<l>ṉalki yōṉē nacaicā ṟōṉṟa</l>
<l>lūḻi vāḻi pūḻiyar perumakaṉ</l>
<l>piṇarmarup piyāṉaic cerumiku nōṉṟāṭ</l>
<l>celvak kaṭuṅkō vāḻi yāta</l>
<l>ṉoṉṉāt tevva ruyarkuṭai paṇittivaṇ</l>
<l>viṭuvar mātō neṭitē ni<gap quantity="19" reason="lost" unit="character"/></l>
<l>pullilai vañcip puṟamati lalaikkuṅ</l>
<l>kalleṉ porunai maṇaliṉu māṅkaṭ</l>
<l>pallūr cuṟṟiya kaḻaṉi</l>
<l>yellām viḷaiyu nelliṉum palavē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l corresp="4">Always stirring [my] big Kiṇai drum with a clear eye, </l>
<l corresp="3">with a new covering with taught leather straps, </l>
<l corresp="2">that looks like the white belly </l>
<l corresp="1">of the sharp-nailed tortoise in the pond, </l>
<l corresp="15a">when I sing: </l>
<l corresp="13">“Having dispelled the poverty of you Vāṇar with smiling wisdom </l>
<l corresp="12">by giving [them] the humble tribute of the kings from enemy regions, </l>
<l corresp="11">[that is,] the many [elephant] bulls of perfect training </l>
<l corresp="10">with large rough broad trunks [and] eminent tusks, </l>
<l corresp="9">who spread in the neighbourhood of the king’s enclosure </l>
<l corresp="5">after having struck the fortification of those who took up opposition, </l>
<l corresp="6">with fragrant cheeks that were bathed in ashes, </l>
<l corresp="7">with flower-dotted bulky necks, </l>
<l corresp="8">stirring and fanning out one after another, </l>
<l corresp="14">may his red feet much flourish.”, </l>
<l corresp="15b">	thinking that is is very good, </l>
<l corresp="16">shall I say “there where those who praise many other things”? </l>
<l>while … </l>
<l>come together, in the pleasing mansion, wide………. (17f.)</l>
<l corresp="18">Wanting to come neat the red feet with perfect anklets, </l>
<l corresp="19">the one with a victorious drum that sounds victoriously, </l>
<l corresp="20">who does not look disparagingly at my smallness </l>
<l corresp="21">shall I look at the fitness of his greatness </l>
<l corresp="22">[and] speak of [his] elephant that is like a hill? </l>
<l corresp="23">Shall I speak of [his] big horse with trimmed mane? </l>
<l corresp="24">Shall I speak of the herd that fills the manger? </l>
<l corresp="25">Shall I speak of the threshing floor with those who thresh by the house? </l>
<l corresp="26">While being strongly confused as by a dream about those that are such, in reality </l>
<l corresp="27">he is the one who granted. Appearance worthy to be longed for. </l>
<l corresp="28">may you live for aeons, great son of the Pūḻiyar. </l>
<l corresp="29">[On?] and elephant with rough tusks [and] fight-lusty sturdy feet, </l>
<l corresp="30">Celvakkaṭuṅkō Vāḻiyātaṉ, </l>
<l corresp="31">Will the enemies, who were in disagreement, having been humbled here under [his] high parasol, </l>
<l corresp="32">not let go for a long time? ….. </l>
<l corresp="34a-c">more than the [grains of] sand in the noisy Porunai </l>
<l corresp="33">that slaps against the out fortification of Vañci with puny leaves (~ the city, not the tree), </l>
<l corresp="36">more than the [grains] of paddy that all ripen </l>
<l>in the fields that encircle the many villages there. (34df.)</l>
</lg>
